@Miles Craghead I guess what I'm saying is a terms of service enforced by best efforts at consistent application of principled rules and users reporting instances of violation is not "mob justice". It's the sane thing to do to combat and mitigate problematic content occurring on these platforms. This idea that twitter conflates right wing content with such other problematic content resulting in a political bias is something that literally Dorsey and the others want to help combat and determine the extent to which it is actually a thing. From what I saw in the hearing, particularly from Dorsey, is that they want to add transparency and accountability to the moderation process and enable third parties to audit. Heck, Dorsey even said let's give users the option to choose recommendation algorithms, open them up to third parties to publish custom recommendation algorithms, or even provide the choice to disable recommendation features altogether. Ultimately that would place the burden of trust at the hands of other entities than twitter, and would serve as a model for the other platforms to follow in suit.
